At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange shifted in negative
After the fall of Tuesday morning, the Prague Stock Exchange rectified its losses.
Transactions with ČEZ stocks reached almost half of the usual daily exchanges.
On Tuesday, from the beginning of the trades, the Prague stock exchange resumed with its fall from the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall of stocks on Wall Street.
The reaction of the market to the result of the vote of the American House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilization plan, is thus also noticeable in us.
Shares fall in Asia
The Asian stock exchanges experienced a dramatic drop on Tuesday, even though the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hong Kong Stock Exchange Hang Seng index lost four percent during exchanges, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the drop to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index following the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong stock market lost 3.8 percent, with markets closed in Shanghai.
Shares on the Sydney Stock Exchange lost more than five percent, but eventually losses were reduced to 4.3 percent.
According to the index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
“Hesitation about the U.S. rescue action will influence financial markets around the world,” said Joseph Yam, chief of the Hong Kong monetary office.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it establishes its monetary policy itself, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd said U.S. lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there would be a risk of the impact of other countries.
The Blood Bath of American Stocks
On Monday, the U.S. House of Representatives rejected the proposed support for the financial system, to which it should have spent up to $700 billion (nearly 12 billion Kč).
Legislators thus rejected the call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should solve the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks experienced a blood bath on Monday and the main stock indices experienced the biggest drop in the last 20 years.
The Dow Jones index lost nearly seven percent, having experienced such a fall for the last time in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it turned out that the proposal was not adopted, it was in a free fall.
Congress ceded: U.S. government can inject $700 billion into banks
The leaders of Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement to the U.S. financial system.
It will be submitted to vote in the beginning of next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a decisive turning point in talks about the adoption of a rescue plan in the form of a $700 billion financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not sure.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and submit it to the vote, Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Said Sunday to Reuters agency Barney Frank, chairman of the House’s banking and financial regulation committee.
According to sources, the plan should be submitted a priori to vote in the Senate on Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement that the rescue plan will be adopted should be a major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market aid can be effective, a "disillusion" will follow.
Paulson: The plan must be effective
“We have made great progress.
We have settled our divergent views on the shape of the market stabilization package," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
She said the final vote could be on Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the lawmakers met with U.S. Finance Minister Henry Paulson, to give the bottom of the government a final form.
It should buy back from financial companies unsold real estate assets that lead financial companies to considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still have to pursue this market recovery plan, but I think we are there," Paulson said.
A Signal for Asian Trade
The global financial crisis has significant impacts on falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, legislators are making sure Congress reaches a definitive agreement on Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trades in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where Congress’ decision could influence Monday’s trades.
For now, however, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two Houses of Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by one or another problem.
Legislators hope that it will be adopted in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still have numerous changes.
The total amount for the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, should be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program does not fulfill its function, it has the possibility of blocking the award of the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush welcomes progress in negotiations
Although the president can put his veto on this decision, Congress, he, has the opportunity to put it in a minority.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finances for the purchase of bad real estate securities, whose value fell, because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
“All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," Republican Senator Judd Gregg said.
U.S. President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman, Tony Fratto, said Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated “the bipartite effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy.”
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate banking committee chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says the legislators have agreed on the responsibility of the financial program, the protection of contributors against losses, the deduction agreement, the progress of the plan on the axis of time.
The new law also provides for the limitation of such golden parachutes for the directors of the companies participating in the program, and it sets up a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
“We have worked very hard on the issue and made significant progress towards a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans,” Paulson said.
The plan also provides aid for real estate owners, who have trouble paying.
The government is expected to negotiate new deposits in the case of mortgages it is going to buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of debtors and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to Patria Finance chief economist David Marek, the proposed plan is a good idea, but its realization will be very difficult.
"And this is due to the fact that it is not known what the mechanism and price of the repurchase of troubled assets will be.
This will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek said this week on the iHNed.cz server.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or at the beginning of next week, Marek says, it is not so important.
“It is much more important that Congressmen agree, as of this week, that they support this plan and that they will devote it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, foreseeing the adoption of the plan, matters most right now," Marek said.
A pushed struggle to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually every mobile device can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can phone.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Nevertheless, there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house a high-end expensive grammophone to put on Maxim Turbulenc's new album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on vinyl disc, and, from a quality point of view, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
Now, if there are stacked vinyl records in your shelves, with rock art, jazz or blues, you at least probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music during travel, that is, compressed music, to say in a simple way - music in MP3.
There are also categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, just as a Pink Floyd fan would have difficulty supporting headphones purchased for twenty crowns on the market.
There are two extremes between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
The life of the batteries is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are unknown functions, of course, of most mobiles.
No current device is as universal as the phone.
In addition to primary functions, telephone calls and SMS sending, it is able to play music and films, record the latter, it has a camera of varying quality and can, for example, even be used for navigation.
And if you take smartphones and communicators into consideration, you will have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can toast meat and no television will take pictures, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal character of the mobile is not without disadvantages.
The larger the number of functions you use, the shorter the interval between two recharges.
And playing music is one of the most important energy clusters.
There are rare mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this number is significantly lower.
In this regard, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are significantly more performing.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, keep in mind that they will only play music for a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get yourself, to be sure, a second recharge for work - this being valid even for more expensive devices.
The problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, as a result of a recharge, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including those with less performance.
Another problem occurs when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited portion of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, music can be recorded directly on the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as drives are concerned, you do not need, except for iPod, any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and players will create a media library ranked by the performer's name, album title, style, or by the user's judgment.
Some devices only display an index with a tree structure, in the way of Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smart phones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a concrete device, you are especially interested in the life of the accumulator, the memory capacity, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If the music is essentially for you, a background noise and if in the day you will listen to it that for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile playing MP3.
Almost every mobile is able to do so today.
You don’t even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
Everyone manages to play MP3 and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have just this format.
It is one of the most widespread formats and besides it, the vast majority of devices can also play music in WMA format.
The AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), however, is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit, from the mobile phone, the corresponding web pages of the operator (or those of another provider) and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical motive.
The supply of operators is unfortunately miserable and is, in most cases, limited to fast-made radio tubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the internet, or even the wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their motive for themselves.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just have to pull the mobile out of your pocket, while you have forgotten your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you still have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which have virtually all mobiles, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three thousand crowns, you can have an already very suitable walkman.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the absence of output for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best phones and the best equipped, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy control.
Really anyone manages to control the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily match the cheapest (cf. our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the similarity of the command with that of a cassette post, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data transmission invoice.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. the Vodafone 527) usually have an exchangeable memory card slot (the type M2, microSD, and so on).
Even considering the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can handle it even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you’re among the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and thus the ease of the control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the farthest in this field.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and a battery lifespan (usually 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will win Czech Republic this year.
Perhaps
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missed for a long time.
We have already mentioned on Mobil.cz repeatedly that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher in us than in the rest of the Union, confirmed it.
Thus, following the last steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to occur - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than in the country.
How is it possible that prices in Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that far exceeds 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who repeatedly stated that there was no room for another operator in the Czech Republic, is choiring with the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network is apparently no longer lucky (besides, now it would hardly find frequencies).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a substantial decrease in prices, to which subsequently also the conventional operators had to react.
Yet, even before the entry of festivities such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, voices similar to those we hear today in Britain were being heard.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could be a real success.
We do not have to go too far to find examples.
In February, we informed you of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
Let us add that behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which owns, among other things, the U:fon in Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more concrete target group.
In order for their operation to be effective, they indeed need much fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are indeed exempt from relatively high costs of construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
This is how virtual operators worldwide profile themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited offer of services.
For example, in Britain, Tesco Mobile offers SMS at least twice as cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on an unusual target group can also be a good advertising shot.
Indeed, this operator is specifically aimed at men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, operating this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say, whether such a concept would be likely to work in our homes as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický said: “The Czech market is relatively small for a segmentary approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of the service offering."
In Czechia, no chance, say mobile operators
Nevertheless, it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual operator in Czechia, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czechia the negotiations are not very promoting.
The launch of Mobilking will rather take place in other countries in our area," said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta Finance Group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any case, not in favour of this idea.
On the contrary, they are trying to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera Group, which would like to take a new step in order to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of enterprise customers, has not hid its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator for a long enough time.
“We want to be able to offer our customers not only fixed, but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we have managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
The future is perhaps promising.
According to non-official information, it seems that we may be able to host the first virtual operator by the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by total silence.
"Right now, we don't think there's room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific in comparison with others.
For the time being, no topic with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us," said Vlastimil Sršeň from the Press Department of Telefonika O2, in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not recorded a viable and bilaterally advantageous project at the moment, which could serve as a basis."
"It is virtually excluded that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
In order to operate within such a limited period of time, we should now have a concrete agreement."
Instead, Vodafone focuses its attention on fulfillment of requests to obtain its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický said: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and especially in the field of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to discover a partner to build a common network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities: in line with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
What is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, the operators know how to understand themselves as thieves at a fair. The chicane accompanying the creation of the U:fon is also evidence of this.
The greatest apparent pressure on the ČTÚ during the creation of the U:fon was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by information available to the public from the ČTÚ web pages.
Nowadays, the U:fon lends itself to serve as an argument not to accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry into the market of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the character of the mobile market in RT, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would subject it, and especially its services, to high demands."
But given the attitude of the mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
“A virtual operator’s entry into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question regarding the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer of potential stakeholders has a priori not shown sufficient interest for the conventional operators," said Kristián Chalupa of the UOHS Department of External Relations.
A statement made in this way would not be a surprise on the part of representatives of operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, take care that no one takes advantage of its position in the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Moreover, as Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, it can be seen that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in prices for mobile phone services."
However, putting pressure in the direction of an honest functioning of the market and a decrease in prices is apparently not part of the interests of the UOHS.
What is actually shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which derives from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises naturally.
Similarly, a price of gasoline strictly identical to all gasoline stations is probably due to the random and hard fight of competition.
"The Office has not identified any signs of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in one way or another.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has an increased corresponding liability for its behaviour in the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators are likely to lack even the telecommunications regulator,” Chaloupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of many points of disagreement.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets developed by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators have a dominant position on such a market.
However, some law experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, it is necessary to obtain, each time, the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator has quite logically the monopoly on its network.
Thus, it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should at least be concerning for the UOHS that three mobile operators are obviously doing the same.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the already mentioned GTS Novera) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Taking responsibility back on the ČTÚ is a fairly common turn in communications, by means of which the ÚOHS washes the hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, it was not possible to introduce in the recently adopted telecommunications law an expansion of ČTÚ's powers in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised improvement in the situation.
The UOHS representatives must know this very well, but their interests are apparently elsewhere.
When nobody looks, it can work
That said, the operation of some sort of virtual pseudo operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies publishing their own price lists for mobile phone services, but the latter are public only in part.
In most cases, it is a question of companies dealing with multi-level marketing.
Specialized mobile phone services are for example offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic turn consists in the fact that the company performs in front of the operator the figure of a classic company customer, who orders a large amount of SIM cards.
As an important customer, she gets special pricing (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such a resale.
"If what you are talking about happened, it could be a breach of the contractual terms that we would consider and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová responded to our question regarding this issue.
Nevertheless, it is rather unlikely that an echo of such an activity has not reached the heads of the mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is opposed to such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them unnecessary profits, and at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický states the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, nevertheless, the services of these companies are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phones is not registered under their names, so they cannot fully dispose of it, as the ordinary customers of the mobile operators."
It is precisely this that should seem strange to ČTÚ.
Furthermore, there is another question to the UOHS.
If mobile operators close their eyes on such a procedure, why do they block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the UOHS has relatively broad powers to unveil such an activity, and if it does not wish to satisfy itself with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we are no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned repeatedly, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in virtually every country where virtual operators appeared, conventional operators sought, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - a market too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that the regulatory bodies intervened in the developed countries, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both by formal measures and by informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators are dealing with this issue like a hot potato that is being disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
Following the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than profitable in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the shaft.
If the backstage information is true and a virtual operator will appear soon, the Czech mobile market may be back in motion.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the UOHS will hardly be able to remain impassible in the face of rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was recorded again by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singing, a choral performance and an instrumental version.
The song is performed by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to all four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek regards Czech national singing as one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose to perform solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I was trying to make sure that the two singers, as well as the choir, had a good dictionary, so that we could understand the lyrics well, that they would sing simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th birthday next year.
The song Kde domov můj sounded for the first time in 1834 on the boards of Stavovské divadlo (the Theatre of States) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des sautiers), a Czech original piece by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by the music of František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the establishment of Czechoslaovakia in 1918, the first couplet naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
