Prague’s public transportation (MHD) will introduce the chip into their ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday, October 1, 2008 will be inscribed in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik as the date on which the first passengers will get into the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about a hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a voucher 30 days or 90 days (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it both registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můsltek, Letráží Holešovice, and Lužišovci.
From yesterday there is also the possibility of buying coupons online on the Dopravní podnik website: www.dpp.cz.
More than 400 people took advantage of the service in the morning.
Those who will start using the online store can forget the ticket offices at the metro stations, where they had to hit long queues in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their coupon online and will be recorded on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (city libraries).
"At these contact points, there is a box office with trained staff at the disposal of the passengers, which will help those interested with the purchase via the internet and, moreover, will record the coupon they bought on their card," said project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
Besides the libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, they recall the tickets composting machines and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Today, the city has five, but by the end of the year, there should be eighty," added Opatrný.
An automaton will control the coupon in the place of the driver
Automates that will work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply enter the Opencard smart card and the coupon previously purchased will register itself on the card.
Electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also around the city.
In other words, in periurban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of central Bohemia to access the capital.
"In the integrated trains in Pražská integrovaná doprava, the controllers are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they determine the temporary and zone validity of coupons," explained the Filip Drápal ticket control of the organization Ropid, which designs the schedules of public transport in Prague.
The periurban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver’s box.
