Sudetens call for a referendum in the United States
In 1945, the Sudet Germans demanded that Šumava be incorporated into the United States.
This results from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vídecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want to at least live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudet Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such a desire.
This follows, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vedecká knihovna.
Germans from Český Krumlov prayed in the letter to the US President not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation well and want to be truly sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," is written in the letter, signed, "People to whom the fate of the Šumava is very important."
Given that the association with Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, regardless attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the US President to take into his hands the protectorate of the Šumava for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has contributed in no way to the victory of the Allies without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter wrote.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is the fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans of Šumava, he would only have to hold, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be a part of the United States, or live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may seem somewhat naive, according to some survivors, given the current knowledge of post-war history, it illustrates well the expectations of the Germans of the Sudetes of the time.
While the Czech Germans had to at least assume that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted to such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to obtain a certain type of autonomy for the Sudets.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German of České Budějovice, engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the English and placed in the capture camp of the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
“They believed that once they returned home, the Czech would benefit them,” Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed he would be expelled from the Republic following the Beneš Decrees.
