In the context of the tragic accident of the Student Agency coach near Padua, Italy, the question arises whether stewards and passengers can travel inside the coach during the journey.
"If one wants to comply with the law strictly and formally, the activity of a steward is contrary to the road traffic law," said Karel Hanzelka, a spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The accident in question, during which a 22-year-old hostess died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the road to the coach.
At that time, the girl was sadly sitting next to the driver on the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats at her disposal.
However, the coach can have an accident, or even abruptly brake, even when the steward serves the coffee or distributes the newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is under its technical sheet equipped with standing seats or not.
If this standing seat equipment is not approved, passengers must remain sitting.
The long-distance Student Agency coaches do not have standing seats; which was confirmed at Aktuálně.cz by the company director Radim Jančura.
"It's a matter that we dealt with with with the ministry and, at first, it prohibited any travel of passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the journey provided they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the steward.
"There is no unambiguous legal interpretation of the role of steward - no legal prescription deals with this role.
On the other hand, no legal requirement does not prohibit the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transportation Act only knows the term vehicle receiver; it does not define its rights and duties," said Hanzelka.
On the contrary, Josef Pokorný, the director of the Department of Road Vehicle Traffic, believes that the law addresses the issue sufficiently.
"It all depends on the fact that the coach has in its approval permission to offer standing seats.
