Rats also have sensations.
A rat or a cockroach fleeing danger, does that mean that he also feels fear?
The neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals also have sensations.
But how can we make sure that he feels the same when he behaves the same way we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without having proof of it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having so far been able to prove it just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter hardly practicable grounds because Hardware does not match.
When a rat is facing a danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it makes the dead, leaks or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I don't believe it.
Two aspects of the structure of the brain make the transposition of our subjective experience to that of animals difficult.
One aspect is that the circuits associated almost always with human consciousness include the prefrontal lateral cortex (due to its participation in short-term memory and in the direction and execution functions).
This vast region is much more developed in human beings than in other primates and appears to be completely absent in other beings.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among which the consciousness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being is even different from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of man: as much of his existence is linked to language, it often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness should not depend on language, it would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, no matter how it is produced, would probably differ much from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, is not allowed to be measured or, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses great problems to us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is next to another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
We could look at the processes of animal consciousness without taking into account their contents, and that's exactly what happened in studies on the short-term memory of primates, especially with the example of visualization.
But in this approach that Christof Koch and Francis Crick followed, we focus more on the nerve correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the prefrontal cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what is the result of emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as the one of fear is activated in a brain aware of its own activity.
