The Bilingual Debate: Immersion in the English Language
In this part of the Education Supervision program, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi discuss the candidates' position on bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a former California student, and former director of the Department of Education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is the co-author of the book "Not as Good as You Think. Why middle classes need to be able to choose their school."
Attracting the favors of Hispanic voters is a complicated business.
Barack Obama’s proposals on education are an interesting example of this.
Obama’s campaign emphasizes that “Afro-American and Latino students are less likely to graduate than white students.”
To combat these differences, Mr. Obama’s education program particularly supports among so many other topics, “bilingual transitional education” for those who learn English.
However, the question arises for Obama is whether his desire to achieve a bilingual education that defends classroom instruction in languages other than English goes beyond his interest in eliminating differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an elementary school in eastern Los Angeles County.
The students at this school are largely Hispanic, and low-income.
More than one-third of the students, consisting of many newcomers, study English.
Among CM1 students, 100% passed the 2008 math State exam, expert level.
Likewise, nearly 93% of students passed the English-of-the-arts exam.
This incredible success was achieved thanks to another ingredient than Mr. Obama’s.
Sixth Street is based on analysis, practice, constant ability assessment and exemplary attitude.
In addition, and here is an example that Mr. Obama could copy, reports Linda Mikels, head of Sixth Street, this school has introduced the English language instruction "full immersion."
Total English immersion focuses on the almost constant use of English in instruction.
Ms. Mikels, contrary to bilingual education, told me "we had a huge success with a student who had just arrived from Mexico, 12 months later, if you went without his class, you wouldn't have had a chance to identify him."
“It works,” she observes, “it worked for us.”
Should Mr. Obama not take an example of the Sixth Street Prep and replicate it in other schools consisting mostly of Hispanic students learning English?
The excellent results achieved by this school speak for themselves; but the policies on education within its party (the Associations for National Education have long supported bilingual education) and its enormous support for bilingual education, obscure the prognosis of Mr. Obama’s response.
Although he is favorable to the fact that immigrants are learning English, Mr. Obama recently regarded this issue as insignificant, when he proclaimed that we must all stop controversy about the wording of English-language laws.
On the contrary, he said, "You must make sure your child speaks Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to eliminate differences, then he should carefully consider the models of education that work, rather than despise them or consider them insignificant.
