In a City at Part, Pride and the Trials of Black Life
Hidden in the development of its immense park, a few miles from the sunny, bright and giant Orlando, lies a quiet small town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, the first entirely black town to be integrated, childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, this description she made in 1935, is no longer so simple to make today." The town with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of goyaves, two schools and no prison."
It has now become a pilgrimage city.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the Zora Festival, which is held every year in Eatonville, to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in various ways, the city she describes- has become touristic thanks to its inclusion in the Florida tour guide published by The Depression-era Federal Writers' Project- remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston was telling that the black rural population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing us so little, doesn't know what he's losing."
Even though it is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has invoked an open dialogue on the theme of race, many here remain cautious of the eyes of foreigners.
“We’re very careful about how to tell the story,” said Hortense Jones, 59, a long-standing resident and the oldest parishioner in the city.
"It must be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and fighting.
It represents both a historic model of a black takeover of power and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of southern black rural culture - sometimes despised, sometimes acclaimed - that recalls the birth of American slavery.
This would explain why residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, whom everyone here calls Hurston.
She presented her hometown to the whole world through sincere, dialect-filled books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide transformed this city, located just at the exit of Route 17, a road that crosses the often forgotten central Florida, which ends in the chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold like a big box in life as well as in literature, Hurston led readers to the property store of Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was subsequently divided into several private parts.
"Passing the road on the left," she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its gardens and well-preserved playgrounds that Howard Miller has always cared for, although he barely knows how to read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells all kinds of beverages and everything that can serve the passengers."
So, in just a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with a self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn’t actually a portrait that everyone enjoyed.
Zora has described the reality well," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's girls whom Hurston immortalized, citing colorless songs performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered as a living and eccentric person, who frequently returned after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town without warning, aboard a large Chevrolet, a cigarette in his mouth and wearing pants here, where even today, we are proud of traditional clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin told, while many mocked her.
“People were always happy to see Zora,” he said.
But he adds further, swinging in his chair from the backyard overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was certainly baptized, that "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a star of literature, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in a tomb in Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no great commemoration, no plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered to the world," said Valérie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A crucial moment came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to move a five-way motorway into the city, replacing Kennedy Boulevard, the main two-way street of the community.
The development of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made while Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period of its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, has put an end to the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 1950s, the dispute over the mixture of races led to hatred at the gates of the community.
“At that time, a bunch of white young people came to throw oranges or objects against people sitting on the side,” Franklin said.
“A lady has even died.”
They threw a watermelon out of their car.”
In a 1955 letter addressed to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, defining his decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorious of my race."
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, although positive in some aspects, has diluted Eatonville cohesion and weakened youth confidence.
"Black kids used to be kissed - I remember - our master was kissed in the morning, and in the evening too," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and Chief Executive Officer of the Eatonville Community Backup, a non-profit group.
This lasted, she added, until the time when teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white - I mean there's a cultural demarcation line here," Nathiri said.
Civil rights, by the way, have created space for many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who have gone beyond harm, such as her, armed with joyful self-confidence and lines of conduct such as: "How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
That exceeds me.”
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited the anonymous tomb of Hurston and began struggling to revive her reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed Hurston biography by Robert E. Hemenway, a true best seller, reintroduced it to the American canons.
The highway project came just when Eatonville's most famous girl had regained her appeal.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors consider her a savior.
The community began to host a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of this highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival’s inauguration two years later, and many come back in January to commemorate it.
After many years, the contee rejected the proposal of the highway.
"The fiasco of the five-way highway, extremely fast, true civic pride," Nathiri said.
Ms. Boyd summarized the whole statement that "Zora saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been a historic city since 1998.
A mono theme library (renamed obviously Hurston) opened in 2006, on a magnificent Kennedy Boulevard, repavé.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time regard itself as a rear back street on a summer rainy day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(Now we have 90 percent of black people.)
Foreigners who come to discover the history of Eatonville, its reason for being, are still treated with caution.
It is necessary to ask permission for most interviews, and certain things—such as the walls of the old church of Eatonville, painted by the white man, illustrating black men in the fields—must not be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a courageous teacher who has a weakness for bright red, are always afraid that their island community will be well understood.
However, given the expansion of the Hurston festival, a certain level of local pride has emerged.
In particular, young people tend to consider Eatonville as Hurston regarded his entire race: beautiful, problematic and everything, neither better nor worse, but as proud, creative, busy, crazy and mixed as other ethnic and racial groups in America.
Franklin’s 18-year-old nephew Edwin Harvey plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or for the police forces, which need additional forces.
And even for the youngest, like Alondra and Alexia Kenon of 11, Winter Park twins, seem to have learned the Eatonville description correctly.
“Most people, who pass through this area there, will think, ‘Oh, this city hasn’t compared anything to others,’” Alondra Kenon said after the mass last Sunday.
But if you stop and take the time to contemplate the story, it’s a very beautiful city.”
