"I photograph the master outside the scene to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to obtain the relaxed appearance of the man or woman.
On the one hand, the artist.
On the other hand, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in those moments unknown to the general public, where one discovers from intimate gestures and stolen eyes artists who do not care to get on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixed in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some stages with singers, dancers and guitarists with this less known side of the artists.
In this project, the photographer resumes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, bigger every day," explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "may be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists able to convey on stage passion, sadness, joy... by captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists, you do not need to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a personality.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allows me to capture with the camera the moments of personality of the flamenco stars.”
In 1997, Bauer began a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and material, remember classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "Music with very traditional roots that evolves and that surprises every day".
It is not about dance or singing in itself, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for essentials and magic was the constant of this work presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has turned into an antology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a collection book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of old athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves photographing the portrait of people, knowing them and being able to enter their lives for a moment or so.
In photography, portrait is the hardest genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters you sometimes don’t know or who leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I still try to make my ideas come true.”
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 of Rue de la Mata (parallel to the Hercules Street), which will be open until October 16th.
