Talking while sleeping
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to the children who talk during their sleep.
The first time that happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn’t matter.
It is a benign disorder of sleep called somnilochya.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course there are more than one speaking at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often linked to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, night enuresis (peeping in bed) or sleeping, but this is not always the case.
As we said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful or overexcited situations.
Anyway, this is a poorly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet little voice, in isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with cries, crying, long speeches...
In case sleepiness becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and in order to get an explanation for this problem.
We said it is a mild disorder, which is why there is no treatment unless it is linked to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is linked to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore, look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down inside.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as the sleepines appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful advice
Don't wake him up.
This is useless because he is unconscious and you would wake him up.
