The Interview - Blood Becomes Safe Again
Héma-Québec was yesterday celebrating the 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice because Héma-Québec has become one of the world’s safest and most effective blood suppliers.
And above all, he regained public trust that had been seriously shaken by the blood scandal contaminated in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, national blood reserves managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the Acquired Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and Hepatitis C Virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this tragedy and public groan, the Government of Canada initiated a public investigation, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, in February 1994, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from happening again.
While Judge Krever was delayed in filing his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec started operations, only 38% of people still had confidence in Quebec's blood system," Dr. Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and work on the ground over the years that followed, we regained public trust,” she said before proudly claiming that in early 2008, nearly 94% of the Quebec population now trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary notes that “trust is something extremely fragile.”
Since its creation, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, many cases of the human form of crazy cow disease were witnessed in Europe, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which has been the stronghold since its foundation in 1998.
“And we didn’t know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gelineau reports, that when it is not known and that a serious disease may result from it, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain leading inevitably to death, exclusion measures are introduced.
In April 1999, the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980 was refused.
Now, a few years ago, it has been shown without any doubt that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle applied was meaningful."
In 1999, a much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid (TAN) tests that allow the presence of the virus itself to be detected directly in the blood of donors and not antibodies to the virus, on which the tests used to date were based.
TANs have shortened the mute period, which spans between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, the specialist explains.
This period was reduced to less than a week.
This has substantially reduced the risk of some donors being infected unknowingly and unable to be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of getting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-infected blood.
In other words, it means it will have to distribute 12 million blood products before anyone gets infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that today one can feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to recover health,” says the chief executive officer of Héma-Québec.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen will emerge in the system.
No later than last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the Western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We need to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Decary continues before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide adequate supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need red blood cell or platelet recharge.
The ageing population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.
However, any healthy person aged 18 years and older who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have travelled to a country where malaria is prevalent, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
“With these 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
The shortages are very rare.
But the members of this donor network need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to give their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to become a regular donor.
"Because today's life is so awkward, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood," says Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered a biomedical waste is filled with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and it is planned to take more than a thousand a year.
We should start proposing for transplants early next year,” said Dr. Decary, who describes this cord blood sampling program as very popular.
"Many moms are disappointed that they cannot access it," because Héma-Québec does not have the means to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
