For, for Barrick Gold, would the best way to lead a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable amounts to prepare their defense and fight, with very uneven weapons, against an army of lawyers supported by the pockets almost bottomless of the mining.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly settlement that will scourge the opposition in addition to frightening anyone who dares to turn to the issue again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before the public opinion that she should have presented her vision of the facts.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are normally done through the exchange of ideas and not with a snare.
Thus, it was enough for the mining to open up its books, files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support to the authors of Black Canada from the back of the hand.
