Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has been shaking Wall Street for months has yet to be endorsed by both chambers of Congress.
It includes: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for default, and a right to look at wages paid to managers of rescued businesses.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Chair Nancy Pelosi, and Republican Representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight yesterday, at the end of a two-day negotiating marathon.
“We have made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets,” Bush administration representative Henry Paulson said.
“Everything has been done in such a way as to shelter the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing Wall Street crisis,” she said.
“That’s the fundamental point: if we don’t do that, trauma, chaos and disturbances in American daily lives will be immense,” said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned the sprint in recent hours because of fear of the effect that a further failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline agreed upon was the opening of the markets this morning.
Late in the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election showed themselves rather favorable to the agreement, but did not fail to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that we were forced to reach this end.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has awarded himself the addition of certain provisions to the agreement, including the one that allows owners to keep their homes and the one on the salary of the executives of state-run companies.
“When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no welcome.
But these measures are necessary,” he commented on the waves of American television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied, "I would like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The broad lines I have read show that this is something we’re all going to have to digest and with which we’re going to be able to move forward.
The option to do nothing is simply not acceptable,” he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to redeem with taxpayers’ money the dubious, risky and unsellable debts of U.S. financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the burst of a real estate bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgage loans (subprimes) before extending to other more widespread forms of credit securities (PCAAs) and leading to a liquidity freeze and bank debt.
It was a group of Republican voters who had the first bill of agreement overturned last week.
It is believed to have come out of this impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only insured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to round the angles for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added that if the government was to bear losses for five years with this program, it could put in place new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first $250 billion tranche, which can be added to another $100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another 350 billion is expected to be endorsed by another Congressional vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will obtain stakes in rescued companies that will pay him dividends in case of profit and that he will be able to sell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the opportunity to delay seizure proceedings for housing attached to the housing loans covered by this plan, as well as to set limits on remuneration and starting allowances to the managers of the affected businesses.
The architects of the plan would like to see it submitted to the House of Representatives vote today, and to the Senate vote on Wednesday.
Despite all their efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will have the green light.
Indeed, votes continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camps.
"Obviously Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House's finance committee, told voters.
“Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not that of taking advantage of taxpayers.”
An animator of a small group in Congress called "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize laureates, wrote to tell us: Congress is asked not to rush and to carefully examine the path to go,” he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, we once again had proof of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for €11.2 billion (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced that it was renouncing to acquire its shipwrecked competitor since it lost 2 billion euros (2.9 billion US) in the U.S. real estate loan crisis.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of the twenty largest European banks and ten largest insurers.
"It's not lost money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, we get a voting right in the bank and influence.
It’s just something that savers and households enjoy now that the weather is announced uncertain.”
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed on track to nationalize another bank ill-run by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all ongoing loans at Bradford and Bringley bank, including more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) of real estate loans.
The Spanish bank Santander announced yesterday that it would buy the UK bank's branches and customer accounts.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after the Northern Rock, that the British government is expected to nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
