The Psychology of Bidding: Why We Spend More Money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the goods.
Researchers in neurology and economics at the University of New York have managed to update the neurological and economic bases of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don’t want to be distant in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that’s why they even prefer to pay an overpriced price.
This research tried to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, while the other group participated in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could earn money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the over-auction of a third, the ensemble under the brain trunk, called striatum, was moving intensely when losing the game.
This part of the brain, alongside several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
This is why, according to the researchers, the price rise is explained by the escape from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economists of this group of researchers pursued financial supervision analyses.
Three groups were bidding against a partner under various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and thus made their placement.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out winning the game, then they would get an additional $15, as a reward.
While the third group received the $15 prior to the auction, the group members also lost that money in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that one focused on victory, while the other focused on failure.
By thus proving the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the players' team "against failure" were willing to make higher bets than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
“These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena seen during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade before the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped eliminate the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor at the Faculty of Economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When Should We See a Doctor?
In the world, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
It is estimated that in Hungary there are one hundred thousand patients carrying the hepatitis virus, but only seven thousand are undergoing treatment because of the fact that often the patients do not know that they are carrying the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to liver infections and caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and yellowness are characteristic, but pathogens and generated diseases differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, according to the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (e.g. contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses by blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travelers, it is recommended to get vaccinated against viruses A and B. There is no C vaccine.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consumption of contaminated foods, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach pain and nausea.
Then a visible yellowness develops on the skin and on the white of the eye, the stools become lighter and the urine becomes darker. Healing can take two to three weeks.
Around the world, every year, one million people die from the most serious form of this disease, such as cancer or liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if not treated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients are not known to have the virus, because the pathogenic gene destroys the liver cells in a deceitful way. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattoos.
Currently, there are around 200 million people worldwide with chronic hepatitis type C.
Since the disease can be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your treating physician as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, thus the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Does anyone who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of a recent research, religious belief would work as a sort of painkiller, which would have already contributed to making the death of Catholic martyrs more tolerable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article that researchers at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment by analyzing to what extent belief in God could influence human tolerance for pain.
As part of this bizarre experience, 12 Catholic believers and so many atheists were subjected to electroshocks, while each of them observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Thanks to a technique of palpation of the human brain, it was also discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments, in which academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university participate.
Specifically, the experiment takes place as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and diffusing electroshocks is fixed on the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to look at two paintings in a sustained manner, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Hermine Lady painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers who originated this experiment hoped that the view of the Virgin Mary evokes a kind of state of faith among the believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its soothing effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time, they received 20 four-part electroshocks successively, while watching either the religious theme painting or the more general theme painting.
Catholics declared that in the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt as "secure," as someone whom we "care" and they "calmed, and peace invaded them."
In view of the religious theme painting, they reported 12% less pain than when they watched Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided they find the appropriate photo.
“We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father,” the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of these researches.
“The practice of faith should change, and in many cases it actually changes our personality,” Wright said.
After these excellent results, there remains only the question of what would be the effect on the regulation of the pain of the subjects if one shows the believers a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would the view of a better quality Virgin Mary cause better results?
