Intelligent car mimics the flight of the bourbon
Which method would be better for developing technologies capable of avoiding an obstacle, other than the imitation of a barrier detector already existing in nature?
For example, the bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, the buzzing bees gave the strategic starting point to Nissan engineers to inspire them on how to design the next generation of barrier detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini-robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C self-roboted controlled system, which it has equipped with bee qualities, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee makes up its own oval-shaped space, which in reality resembles our secure protective shell - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the brand's research and development department and technological public relations.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a primary role, since it is capable of seeing in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To imitate the functions of the facet eye, the engineers approached the idea of the laser distance meter.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters from the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the onboard microprocessor, which transforms it into an immediate avoidance maneuver.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, mimicking the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it by an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any existing system, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If it weren't so, the mini auto robot wouldn't be able to react fast enough to avoid the obstacle," said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and Robotic Car Project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and inner layer of the protective envelope, a layer where the collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must take place in a blink of an eye.
In contrast to bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two dimensions, and only in the direction in which the wheels can rotate.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use the rotary movement, acceleration as well as slowdown as manoeuvres at the disposal of the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lighter lithium polymer batteries with a higher energy concentration, which makes their life longer than in the Lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the intelligent instinctive reaction that is primordial, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process and react to a few incoming signals per second.
It is not necessary to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous manoeuvres, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
We do not need memory for gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards the design of an instant avoidance technology, which Nissan estimates will enter mass-made cars in the next 10 years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles on his way.
