Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007, according to the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export sales prices rose 1.1 percent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased 3.9 percent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 per cent from the previous month, and by 3.2 per cent from the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices increased only to a lesser extent: 0.1 percent compared to the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry have only experienced a tiny 0.1 percent increase compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 percent), with in the first place the manufacturing of bags and belts with a monthly rise of 4.6 percent, then the footwear production with a monthly rise of 2.5 percent.
The higher prices of plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a substantial monthly rise in prices in the chemical and product manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in oil processing (1.4 percent), electrical machinery and appliance manufacturing (0.9 percent), as well as a minimum increase in wood processing (0.1 percent).
The prices of paper production, publishing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the processing industry saw a rise, between 0.2 percent and 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supplies sectors, representing a significant role in domestic industrial operations, prices increased by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the effect of rising gas prices put in place by authorities since July 1.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales of the processing sectors, the prices of the oil processing sector had the most significant increase (32.4 percent).
In the metallurgical manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2 per cent, while in the important field of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11 per cent.
Price decreases have occurred in the textile and textile manufacturing sectors (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacturing of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In other sectors of the processing industry, price increases evolved between 0.6 percent and 9.1 percent.
Throughout the processing industry, prices increased by 10.2 percent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors exceeded 18.7 percent of the previous year.
Among the domestic trade groups and according to sector allocation, in August, the earnings-on-initiator sectors showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 percent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent processing did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and materials production sectors for subsequent processing (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-initiating sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Industrial export prices, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, while they fell 3.9 percent over 12 months.
In one month, our national payment method weakened by 1.7 per cent from the euro, and 7.1 per cent from the dollar; compared to August 2007, it increased by 7.5 per cent from the euro and 15.9 per cent from the dollar.
