Mp3 player pointed to the finger, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to full-volume music for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players can cause permanent hearing injury.
This is what the European Commission announced, which, in a statement issued in Brussels, cites the opinion of the Scientific Committee on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific report - we read in the note - it shows that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to full-volume music using portable music devices, for more than an hour a day and a week, risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and full-volume mobile phones can unconsciously damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” said Meglena Kuneva.
"According to scientific data, this is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
What matters most is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public.
In addition, we need to re-examine existing control systems in the light of scientific opinion, so that they are fully effective and can follow up on new technologies."
Brussels requested the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intense use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to noise generated by them.
"Scientists concluded that there are good reasons to worry, and that the European Commission will now discuss with Member States and other stakeholders what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents against noise exposure from portable music devices and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is a growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to properly limit these data using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration.
The Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to full-volume music (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on maximum noise allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for extended periods of time risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity after 5 years.
This interests 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified to around 2.5 and 10 million people in the U.E.
