In the United States as well as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been overwhelmed for some time, to the extent that, in the new climate, they solidify and reveal themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary recovery, of the double sovereign state category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, indeed, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions which, of course, have close relations with abroad, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global but politically it is almost only national here.
Political internationalization seems really out of play or has little to say: the obvious evidence is provided to us by the European Union, which, shared as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, cannot decide on any common political line.
