Farewell old cinema Paradiso, the towns evoke the historic halls.
Historic cinemas close in favor of Multiplexes.
“A city without cinemas is a blind city, it’s like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore illustrates well what is happening in the great urban centres of Italy, but also in the cities of the province,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth of large multirooms on the outskirts, and the death of consumption of monorooms in the central areas of the cities, is one of the major events that seems to us inevitable and indisputable; in addition, it has all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear, these are often historic places and loaded with memory, "it is as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we have shared a bit of way and so many emotions for always" can be observed by the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, which offered to Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix of a Cannes jury.
The figures provided by Anec, the main merchant association, mean everything: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and it is the halls of the main cities that have mostly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia Romaine is at the top with 82 mono cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The evidence that the first responsible for their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, since it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-room cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," notes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but it should still be guaranteed the survival of those that already exist, because when a room closes in a city, these friends are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexs.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit to merchants: the state’s previous debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, it would take between 16 and 18 million euros a year.
Notice the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, worried about these closures, decided to resolve the situation by signing a protocol between the City Hall and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote the cinemas mono rooms of the historic centers and peripherals.
Among the standards provided are tax facilitation measures for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: viewers will be able to enter the limited traffic area, and will have special rates for parking and some parking lots.
"I like this initiative," notes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by putting in place other measures.
However, it is obvious that to contrast the super power of multiplex, traditional rooms also need to improve the sound and image quality, as today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Bagheria Supercinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" to which I was already thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn from the other side to not see the signs blackened by the dust.
